  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Why aren't there more apps like Word Lens?",
  "response": "Word Lens was an innovative app that used augmented reality (AR) to translate text in real-time using a smartphone's camera. While it was a pioneering app in its field, there are several reasons why we may not see an abundance of similar apps:\n\n1. **Complexity of Development**: Building an app that requires real-time image recognition and machine translation involves advanced technology and significant resources. The combination of computer vision, natural language processing, and AR can be complex to implement and optimize.\n\n2. **Cost**: Developing sophisticated apps like Word Lens can be expensive. It requires investment in technology, skilled personnel, and extensive testing. Many developers may not have the resources to create a high-quality product.\n\n3. **Market Demand**: While there is a niche market for real-time translation apps, the overall demand may not be sufficient to justify the investment for many developers. Companies might prefer to focus on more versatile apps that serve broader purposes.\n\n4. **Competition from Established Players**: Major tech companies like Google and Microsoft have substantial resources to develop and maintain similar technologies. They may dominate the market, making it challenging for smaller developers to compete.\n\n5. **User Experience**: Real-time translation requires high accuracy and reliability. Users expect instant results that can be dependent on the quality of the camera, lighting conditions, and text clarity. Ensuring a consistently positive user experience can be difficult.\n\n6. **Integration and Functionality**: Many apps tend to focus on broader functionalities that encompass translation along with other features, rather than purely real-time translation. This can dilute the offerings specifically focused on AR translation.\n\n7. **Evolving Technology**: The technology behind augmented reality and machine learning is continually evolving. Developers may prefer to wait for further advancements before investing in new applications to ensure they can leverage the latest capabilities.\n\nDespite these challenges, advancements in technology may lead to the emergence of more apps in this space in the future, particularly as AR continues to gain traction and accessibility improves.",
